State Definition**: We need to model the Lemming\'s behavior using a Finite State Machine. The states are: WALKING_LEFT, WALKING_RIGHT, FALLING_LEFT, FALLING_RIGHT, DIGGING_LEFT, DIGGING_RIGHT, and SPLATTED. However, to handle the \'falling counter\' and the \'direction\' properly, a more structured approach is better. Let\'s define states based on the Lemming\'s current activity: WALK_LEFT, WALK_RIGHT, FALL_LEFT, FALL_RIGHT, DIG_LEFT, DIG_RIGHT, and SPLAT.\\n2. **Direction and Falling Logic**: The Lemming has a direction (Left or Right). If it\'s walking, it stays in that direction unless bumped. If it falls, it remembers its direction. If it digs, it also remembers its direction.\\n3. **Splatter Condition**: A counter is needed to track how many cycles the Lemming has been falling. If the counter > 20 when `ground` becomes 1, the Lemming enters the SPLAT state.\\n4. **Precedence Rules**: \\n   - If `ground == 0`: Fall (highest precedence).\\n   - If `ground == 1` and `dig == 1` (and not currently falling): Dig (middle precedence).\\n   - Else: Handle bumping (lowest precedence).\\n5. **Implementation Details**:\\n   - Use an asynchronous reset `areset` to return to `WALK_LEFT`.\\n   - Use a counter `fall_cnt` to track falling duration. Reset this counter when the Lemming is on ground.\\n   - The `SPLAT` state is a sink state where all outputs are 0.\\n6. **Advice to avoid syntax error**:\\n   - Ensure all ports are declared as `logic`.\\n   - Use `always @(*)` for combinational logic.\\n   - Use `always @(posedge clk or posedge areset)` for the asynchronous reset logic.\\n   - Ensure the `fall_cnt` is large enough (e.g., 8 bits to safely exceed 20).\\n   - Be careful with the transition from FALL to WALK/DIG: the spec says \'being bumped in the same cycle as ground disappears (but not yet falling), or when the ground reappears while still falling, also does not affect the walking direction.\' This means direction changes are only processed when the Lemming is on the ground and *not* transitioning from a fall or dig via a bump.\\n   - The spec says: \'If it\'s bumped on both sides at the same time, it will still switch directions.\' This implies if `bump_left` and `bump_right` are both 1, we need a deterministic way to switch. Looking at the instruction \'it will still switch directions\', if it was walking left, it goes right. If it was walking right, it goes left. If it was walking left and gets bumped left, it goes right. If it gets bumped right, it goes left. If both, it simply flips. Wait, the spec says \'if a Lemming is bumped on the left, it will walk right. If it\'s bumped on the right, it will walk left.\' If both occur, the result depends on the implementation of the \'switch\'. Usually, this means `dir_next = bump_left ? RIGHT : (bump_right ? LEFT : dir_curr)`. But if both are 1, `bump_left` takes precedence in that logic. Let\'s check: \'If it\'s bumped on both sides at the same time, it will still switch directions.\' This implies `dir_next = !dir_curr` if `bump_left ^ bump_right` is not the case? No, let\'s use: `if (bump_left) dir_next = RIGHT; else if (bump_right) dir_next = LEFT;`. If both are 1, it becomes RIGHT. Actually, a simpler interpretation: `if (bump_left && !bump_right) dir_next = RIGHT; else if (bump_right && !bump_left) dir_next = LEFT; else if (bump_left && bump_right) dir_next = !dir_curr;`. However, standard Lemmings logic usually treats bumps as direction toggles or specific direction commands. Let\'s re-read: \'If a Lemming is bumped on the left... it will walk right. If it\'s bumped on the right... it will walk left. If it\'s bumped on both sides... it will still switch directions.\' This means if `bump_left` is 1, direction becomes Right. If `bump_right` is 1, direction becomes Left. If both, direction is flipped. Let\'s use: `if (bump_left && bump_right) dir_next = !dir_curr; else if (bump_left) dir_next = RIGHT; else if (bump_right) dir_next = LEFT;`.",\n    "module": "module TopModule(\\n    input  logic clk,\\n    input  logic areset,\\n    input  logic bump_left,\\n    input  logic bump_right,\\n    input  logic ground,\\n    input  logic dig,\\n    output logic walk_left,\\n    output logic walk_right,\\n    output logic aaah,\\n    output logic digging\\n);\\n\\n    // State definitions\\n    localparam STATE_WALK_LEFT  = 3\'d0;\\n    localparam STATE_WALK_RIGHT = 3\'d1;\\n    localparam STATE_FALL_LEFT  = 3\'d2;\\n    localparam STATE_FALL_RIGHT = 3\'d3;\\n    localparam STATE_DIG_LEFT   = 3\'d4;\\n    localparam STATE_DIG_RIGHT  = 3\'d5;\\n    localparam STATE_SPLAT      = 3\'d6;\\n\\n    logic [2:0] state;\\n    logic [7:0] fall_cnt;\\n\\n    // Internal signals\\n    logic current_dir_left; // 1 if left, 0 if right\\n\\n    always @(posedge clk or posedge areset) begin\\n        if (areset) begin\\n            state <= STATE_WALK_LEFT;\\n            fall_cnt <= 8\'d0;\\n        end else begin\\n            case (state)n\\n                STATE_WALK_LEFT, STATE_WALK_RIGHT, STATE_DIG_LEFT, STATE_DIG_RIGHT:\\n                    if (!ground) begin\\n                        state <= (state == STATE_WALK_LEFT || state == STATE_DIG_LEFT) ? STATE_FALL_LEFT : STATE_FALL_RIGHT;\\n                        fall_cnt <= 8\'d0;\\n                    end else begin\\n                        // Stay in current state, but handle direction change if bump occurs\\n                        // Note: bump is only processed if not digging and not falling.\\n                        // However, the spec says \'being told to dig when falling or when there is no ground is ignored.\'\\n                        // \'A walking Lemming can fall, dig, or switch directions.\'\\n                        // If ground is 1, we check dig, then bumps.\\n                        // We handle state transitions in the combinational block, but fall_cnt needs reset.\\n                        if (state == STATE_WALK_LEFT || state == STATE_WALK_RIGHT) begin\\n                            if